Dies nondum decem intercesserant, cum, etc. Similar inversions are common in English: the two actions are independent, the temporal clause being put first as an independent sentence, while what is logically the principal clause is subjoined with cum. Cp. ἓ72, Unus et alter dies intercesserat, cum res parum certa videbatur : ἓ 83.

For optime many MSS. give optima, but on the whole the former is to be preferred. Lambinus suggested con- firmata for confirmato. Sassia’s mind is now ‘fully con- firmed in her expectations'3 she is quite confident in her prospect of married happiness. Classen thinks that what Sassia looked forward to was the ‘amplior hereditas ’ that would accrue on the death of the children3 but this seems far· fetched. It was rather Oppianicus who wanted her money. cp. qui pecuniam Sassiae concupivisset above, and propter pecuniam in what follows.
